@node Do_czego "What is InBoot?"

This is the program to install bootblocks on disk. By use of it You can easy
and quick way install on disk, remove, save or read from file any
bootblocks.

The program can write bootblock as an executable file.

The program can install bootblocks in all current filesystems (to system
3.0). Can also work with highdensity disk drives (1.76 Mb).

The program is localized. Persons who have sytem 2.1+ can use the polish
version of program.

InBoot have ARexx port and built in On-Line Help!

Program doesn`t need any non standard libraries. All needed are available on
disk with Workbench.
@endnode

@node uruchom "Starting program"

The program is runnable from Shell (or CLI) or from Workbench.

@{fg fill}In shell You can add some parameters to run:@{fg text}

 PUB= After keyword "PUB=" You have to enter name of the public screen for
      the program. Not using of this parameter means standard public screen
      (default "Workbench").

      @{fg highlight}@{b}@{u}Attention!@{uu} Name of the screen is case sensitive!!@{fg text}@{ub}

 X=   After keyword "X=" You enter horizontal position for left top corner
      for window. Not using of this parameter means middle of screen.

 Y=   Same as above for vertical position. Not using of this parameter means
      position below screen tiltle bar.

 SX=  Horizontal coordinate for left top corner used by @{"iconify" link uôpienie} gadget.
      Default: SX=X.

 CENTRE  This directive sets Y param to center of screen.

 BOOTPATH= After keyword You have to put path for Your directory with
           bootblocks. Default is "PROGDIR:Bootblocks".

 AGDOCPATH= After keyword You have to put path to documentation. Default
            "PROGDIR:"

Here is the InBoot parameters pattern for CLI (same as returned after run
with `?` parameter).

PUB/K,X/N/K,Y/N/K,SX/N/K,CENTRE/S,BOOTPATH/K,AGDOCPATH/K

@{fg fill}If You start program from Workbench@{fg text} the params can be included by adding
them to ToolTypes of program icon. The only difference is keyword PUB
changed to PUBSCREEN.
@endnode

@node help "Internal On-Line Help"

The program have internal help system in AmigaGuide standard. By press of
`Help` key this page will appear. Don`t forget that in `Libs:` dircetory You
need amigaguide.library, and in directory pointed by parameter @{"AGDOCPATH" link uruchom 30} is
documentation "InBoot.guide". If one of these things missing the On-Line
Help will not work and the message about error will appear. Help window is
ascynchronic. This means that not locks the program and You still be able to
choose it`s options. If mouse pointer points a gadget and You press `HELP`
the information about gadget function will appear. You not need to close old
help window to get new help - You got it in the same one. On-Line Help
doesn`t work in windows "About" and "View", because I think that You won`t
need it. if You have system 3.0 or newer use for best results
amigaguide.library in version 39 because have more features (colors, bolds,
underlines etc.)
@endnode

@node funkcje "Program options"

You can use the program with mouse or keyboard. Options are fitted in
program window as gadgets (buttons). Underlined letter in gadget means
keyboard shortcut. Available options are:

@{" Quit                  " link koniec}
@{" About                 " link About}
@{" Mode                  " link Mode}
@{" Drive                 " link Drives}
@{" System                " link System}
@{" Install               " link Install}
@{" Iconify               " link Uôpienie}
@{" Information window    " link info}
@{" Load                  " link Load}
@{" Save                  " link Save}
@{" Save executable       " link SaveExe}
@{" Read                  " link Read}
@{" View                  " link View}
@endnode

@node koniec "Quit"

To quit program You have to choose close gadget. This is standard system
gadget in left top corner of window. The keyboard shortcut is `Esc` key.
@endnode

@node About "About"

Option shows user small information about program, author and name of ARexx
port.
@endnode

@node Mode "Mode"

We are able to choose program work mode. By now available are:

1. Boot - program generates bootblock itself
2. NoBoot - program deletes bootblocks
3. Buffer - program works with buffer

In buffer mode we have active:

@{" Load          " link Load}
@{" Save          " link Save}
@{" Read          " link Read}
@{" View          " link View}

In this work mode we are able to copy bootblock from disk to disk, write it
to file, read from file or just view it`s contents.
@endnode

@node Drives

By this gadget You are able to choose drive You want to operate on it. You
can to it by click on position or by keyboard shortcut for forward or with
`Shift` for backward.
@endnode

@node System

The program lets You to change the filesystem, but better don`t use it
because the program changes it automatically (checks inserted disk and sets
right system). You can change the filesystem only when disk is empty - else
there will be several confilicts with files and new filesystem.
@endnode

@node Install

Gadget to install bootblocks. In different work modes will generate, remove
or just install bootblock with buffer.

The gadget is disabled when there is no disk in selected drive, the disk is
write protected, unformatted or just buffer is empty (if program work mode
is @{"buffer" link mode}). If an error occured the message about it is available in
@{"information window" link Info}.
@endnode

@node Uôpienie "Iconify"

After choose of system gadget "zoom" (near window depth gadget) the window
size will be minimalized and program will asleep. Another press of the
gadget will awake program.
@endnode

@node info "Information window"

Information window is place under gadget @{"About" link About}. The main idea is to:
show information about inserted disk. From left:
 - name of choosed drive
 - type of inserted disk (DD or HD)
 - runnable bootblock (Boot) or not (NoBoot)

If there is no disk in choosed drive or in drive is write-protected disk in
window will appear information about it. In window could appear message
"Error!!!" and means that in drive is unformatted disk.

In window are displayed also informations about errors in installation of
bootblock.
@endnode

@node Load

Option loads bootblock from file into buffer. After choose the filerequester
will appear and user have to choose bootblock.
@endnode

@node Save

Option writes bootblock to disk as file. After choose option the
filerequester will appear and user will have to enter the name of file. If
file named same already exists You will get message.
@endnode

@node SaveExe "Save Executable"

Option writes bootblock from buffer to disk as executable file (runnable
from dos or WorkBench). Several bootblocks can make GURU when You run them.
Don`t blame InBoot fot that - the bootblocks are badly coded. The bootblocks
can work only in PAL and NTSC.
@{b}
The author of above option is Zbigniew Trzcionkowski (Zeeball/Apathy).@{ub}
@endnode

@node Read

Option loads bootblock from disk and stores it in buffer. There is also
possibility to read bootblock from executable bootblock generated by InBoot.
Option is not active when there is no disk in choosed drive.
@endnode

@node View

After choose of the option program will open second window and display in it
the bootblock from buffer. Option uses system font to display the contents
of buffer.
@endnode

@node ARexx "ARexx port"

The program contains internal command set to use by ARexx port. These
commands gives same like almost all GUI functions.

InBoot creates communication port entitled "2b_InBoot_rexx". This name is
displayed also in About gadget (if not - ARexx port is not active). To tell
ARexx destination of commands you have to explain it by command: "Address
'2b_InBoot_rexx'". Don`t forget that You need also activated ARexx server
(program RexxMast).

Commands syntax of is:

COMMAND arguments

The arguments between `[` and `]` are not needed. The commands returns
results of it`s operations in variables RC and RESULT. Variable RC is
reserved to error handling. The standard values are: 10 - means syntax
error, 5 means that command is impossible to execute and 0 if everything
went ok. To get results from InBoot in variable RESULT You have to add at
the begin of the script line: "OPTIONS RESULTS". This will inform ARexx that
we want to know returned things. If commnad not returns anything variable
RESULT will be set to text `RESULT`.The commands are not case sensitive.

Here are accepted commands:

@{" Drive           " link DriveRexx}
@{" Help            " link HelpRexx}
@{" InBoot To Back  " link BackRexx}
@{" InBoot To Front " link FrontRexx}
@{" Info            " link InfoRexx}
@{" Install         " link InstallRexx}
@{" Load            " link LoadRexx}
@{" Mode            " link ModeRexx}
@{" Quit            " link QuitRexx}
@{" Read            " link ReadRexx}
@{" Save            " link SaveRexx}
@{" Save Executable " link SaveExeRexx}
@{" System          " link SystemRexx}
@{" View            " link ViewRexx}
@{" Zoom            " link ZoomRexx}
@endnode

@node DriveRexx "Drive"

DRIVE [drive]

Command changes current drive or checks for the current one. If parameter
not included the command will return in variable RESULT the name of the
current drive (`DF0:`, `DF1:`, etc.). The argument should be: `DF0:`,
`DF1:`, `DF2:`, `DF3:`. If given drive not installed the command will return
5 in variable RC. The names must be given in format like above (big letters,
``).

Arguments:
        drive - drive name ('DF0:', 'DF1:', 'DF2:', 'DF3:'), or nothing

Results:
        RESULT - name of current drive
        RC - 10 - syntax error, 5 - no drive, 0 - success.

Example:
        Drive
        Say 'Drive:' result
        Drive 'DF1:'
@endnode

@node HelpRexx "Help"

HELP

Command opens help system on the @{"main page" link main} of the documentation.

Przykîad:
        Help
@endnode

@node BackRexx "InBoot To Back"

INBOOT TO BACK

Command hides InBoot window behind rest of windows on it`s public screen.

Example:
        InBoot To Back
@endnode

@node FrontRexx "InBoot To Front"

INBOOT TO FRONT

Puts screen with InBoot to front, puts InBoot window to front and activates
it.

Example:
        InBoot To Front
@endnode

@node InfoRexx "Info"

INFO argument

Command depending on the argument returns results in variable RESULT.

Arguments:

Buffer - Checks the buffer and returns 0 if empty, 1 if full

Bootable - Checks disk for executable bootblock and returns 1 if executable
           or 0 if non executable. If no disk variable RC will return 5.

Disk - Checks for type of disk (DD or HD) and returns text strings "DD" or
       "HD". If no disk nothing will be returned.

Protect - Checks write protection of disk and returns 1 if write protected,
          0 if enabled or 5 if no disk.

Pubscreen - Will return the name of the public screen with InBoot.

Version - Will return version number of program. Should be useful if new
          Arexx commands will appear if next InBoots. Gives possibility to
          write more user friendly scripts.

Results:
        RESULT - wanted informations
        RC - 0 success, 5 if program could not give needed informations.

Example:
        Info Version
        Say 'InBoota version:' result
@endnode

@node InstallRexx "Install"

INSTALL

Command installs bootblock on disk (same like gadget @{"Install" link install}). If You want
to install bootblock from buffer You have to change working mode by @{"MODE" link moderexx}
command. If installation failed will be returned 5 in variable RC. If You
want to know why installation failed You have to check disk status by @{"INFO" link inforexx}
(and buffer if needed).

Result:
        RC - 0 if instllation successful, 5 if not.

Example:
        Install
@endnode

@node LoadRexx "Load"

LOAD [filename]

Command reads bootblock into the buffer. If argument not included the
filerequester will appear like from @{"gadget" link load}. Command returns result in
variable RC. The values are 0 for succes, 5 if reading of is impossible
(maybe not exists, or is damaged) or 1 if user pressed "Cancel" in
filerequester.

Arguments:
        filename - filename with full path

Result:
        RC - 0 if success, 1 if user abadoned by "Cancel", 5 if file can not
             be loaded.

Example:
        Load 'ram:bootblock_1'
@endnode

@node ModeRexx "Mode"

MODE [mode]

Command changes working mode of program. If parameter not included command
will return current set of mode in variable RESULT. Modes of work are:
   0 - Boot
   1 - No Boot
   2 - Bufor

Arguments:
        node - Mode (from 0 to 2)

Results:
        RESULT - Number of selected mode
        RC - 0 success, 10 wrong parameter

Example:
        Mode
        Say 'mode no:' result
        Mode 2
@endnode

@node QuitRexx "Quit"

QUIT

Commands closes the program.

Example:
        Quit
@endnode

@node ReadRexx "Read"

READ

Command reads bootblock from disk. If impossible to do will be returned 5 in
variable RC.

Result:
        RC - 0 if success, 5 if fault.

Example:
        Read
@endnode

@node SaveRexx "Save"

SAVE [filename]

Command writes bootblock from buffer. if argument not included the
filerequester will appear like from an @{"gadget" link save}. Command returns result in
variable in RC. The values are 0 for success, 5 when file can not be writen
or 1 if user pressed "Cancel" in filerequester.

Arguments:
        filename - filename with full path.

Result:
        RC - 0 if success, 1 if user abadoned by "Cancel", 5 if file can not
             be writen.

Example:
        Save 'ram:bootblock_1'
@endnode

@node SaveExeRexx "Save"

SAVE EXECUTABLE [filename]

Command writes bootblock from buffer as executable file. If argument not
included the filerequester will appear like this from the @{"gadget" link saveexe}. Command
returns result in variable RC. The values are 0 if success, 5 if file can
not be writen or 1 if user pressed "Cancel" in filerequester.

Arguments:
        filename - filename with full path

Result:
        RC - 0 if success, 1 if user abadoned by "Cancel", 5 if file can not
             be writen.

Example:
        Save Executable 'ram:bootblock.exe'
@endnode

@node SystemRexx "System"

SYSTEM [name]

Command changes filesystem of disk. If name not gived the command will
return in variable RESULT current system or "BAD" if the disk is not
formatted.

Arguments:
        name - name of filesystem (OFS or FFS)

Result:
        RESULT - name of current filesystem
        RC - 0 if success, 5 if disk not formatted, 10 if wrong argument.

Example:
        System FFS
        System
        Say 'name of filesystem:' result
@endnode

@node ViewRexx "View"

VIEW

Command displays buffer (like from @{"gadget" link View}). If impossible to execute will
be returned 5 in variable RC. Displaing is impossible only when the buffer
is empty.

Result:
        RC - 0 if success, 5 if display of buffer is impossible.

Example:
        View
@endnode

@node ZoomRexx "Zoom"

ZOOM [mode]

Command smalls program window to the minimal. If we not give parameter,
command giveout current setting.

Arguments:
        mode - 0 - normal size of program window
             - 1 - smalled size of program window

Result:
        RESULT - current set of (0 or 1)
        RC - 0 if success, 10 if wrong parameter.

Example:
        Zoom 1
        Zoom
        Say 'Zoom:' RESULT
@endnode

@node Wymagania "Requirements, libraries, technical stuff"
@{fg fill}@{b}
Requirements:@{fg text}@{ub}
 - any Amiga model,
 - an Asl.library v38+,
 - system 2.04 or newer,
@{fg fill}@{b}
For best results:@{fg text}@{ub}
 - system 3.0+,
 - locale.library (localization),
 - amigaguide.library (On-Line Help),
 - rexxsyslib.library (ARexx port),
 - screennotify.library
 - xvs.library (bootblock viruses)
@endnode

@node Future "What in future?"

 I want to add to the program some options:

  - analyzing of bootblocks
@endnode

@node History "History of program"

version 0.2       18.08.1996     o First public release.

version 0.4       21.10.1996

     - I added reading of parameters from an icon,
     - I added four new parameter X, Y, SX, CENTRE,
     - I added iconifing option,
     - I added keyboard handling,
     - Removed possibility of run two same programs,
     - Program needs to run system 2.04.

version 0.5       01.12.1996

     - I wrote procedure writing bootblock,
     - I automatized gadget Boot,
     - In information window appears more informations.

version 1.0       26.12.1996

     - I added possibility of writing and reading of bootblock
       from file
     - Program uses reqtools.library

version 1.1       12.01.1997

     - I added option to show bootblock in buffer,
     - Note about program is now a separated gadget (earlier was showed
       after press of quit gadget),
     - I added changing the pointer to busy (clock) when the program
       is making something
     - I corrected a bug making GURU after write of bootblock to file
       and reading it again.

version 1.2       04.11.1997

     - The program can calculate bootblock checksum,
     - Adapted for BlaBla internal standards,
     - Samll changes in GUI (removed gadget "Boot", added to gadget "Mode"
       position "No Boot", so GUI is looks nicer),
     - I added localization of program,
     - I changed option "About" - in information window is now also displayed
       a BlaBla logo.

version 1.3       25.11.1997

     - I added so called On-Line Help,
     - I added ARexx port.

version 1.4      10.01.1998

     - I corrected scaling.
     - Removed bug making GURU,
     - Documentation could be in any directory (I added parameter AGDOCPATH),
     - To display bootblock contents is used system font (non proportional).

version 1.5      24.05.1998

     - The program have support for "screennotify.library",
     - I fixed small bugs.

version 1.6      27.12.1998

     - I added option to write bootblocks as executable files.

version 1.7      02.08.1999     o Current version of program.

     - I added support for "xvs.library",
     - Gadget to change filesystem now conatins all filesystems recognized
       by OS 3.1.

@endnode

@node BlaBla "BlaBla Info"

@{b}@{fg shine}BlaBla@{ub}@{fg text} is a Polish biggest system programmers group. We make the system
friendly programms. We guarantee that our programs will run on almost every
machine (@{fg fill}Amiga@{fg text} of course), including future ones. All our programs are
running in multitasking, and all of them are PD, Freeware, or Shareware.

Our organisation has a few members (we "absorb" only good programmers), an
own e-mail address. Our newest productions you can find in Aminet (their
names are starting by "2b_" sign) and in our PD library called "@{b}Polware@{ub}".
Our texts, articles you can also find in our disk-mag "@{b}Izviestia@{ub}" (sorry,
in Polish!).

@{b}@{fg shine}BlaBla@{ub}@{fg text} group is well-known in Poland, and programs signed with "Blabla" are
for sure very good. We made many productions, we help many young
programmers, we write articles to Polish edition of @{b}Amiga Magazine@{ub}, @{i}we try
to do all, for our beloved computer - Amiga!@{ui}

BlaBla page: http://www.blabla.w.pl
E-mail: blabla@zskl.p.lodz.pl
@endnode

